<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-761-978  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 761 978.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Journal of Systems Management  August 1990 v41 n8 p21(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Maintaining profitable continuity. (Management Information RoundTable) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Reitzfeld, Milt.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>All businesses, regardless of their size, must maintain profitablecontinuity: small businesses must create new jobs to allow theeconomy to expand, and large businesses must assure that theirorganizations have a place in future international markets ascompetition intensifies.andP;  Preparation is the key to maintainingprofitable continuity by anticipating changing markets, newbreakthroughs and crises on the horizon.andP;  An example is the risein occupational illnesses caused by working at computerworkstations and keyboard positions known as Repetitive StrainInjuries (RSI) as well as other technology-induced health risks,such as cancer-causing radiation emissions from computer monitors.andO;Another is the shortage of educated workers expected in the futureas demand for technically qualified workers increases and thesupply diminishes.andP;  How to prepare for these and othercontingencies is discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Occupational HealthBusiness PlanningOutlook.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>